{
  "title": "Modeling 'Long Dwell' Behavior to Improve LinkedIn Feed Engagement",
  "summary": "This article discusses the development and implementation of an innovative model to predict 'long dwell' behavior on the LinkedIn Feed. The model addresses challenges such as noisy dwell time signals, lack of adaptive thresholds, and biases introduced by static thresholds. By using a binary classifier that predicts whether a user will spend more time on a post compared to a specific percentile of similar posts, LinkedIn has improved user engagement metrics, including sessions, overall time spent, and time spent per post. The model is dynamic, adapting to changes in user behavior and content distribution, and has shown statistically significant positive improvements in online A/B testing.",
  "key_points": [
    {
      "title": "Importance of Dwell Time",
      "content": "Dwell time is a critical indicator of content quality and relevance, especially for passive consumers who do not engage explicitly. It provides broader coverage compared to explicit signals like likes, comments, and shares."
    },
    {
      "title": "Previous Dwell Optimization",
      "content": "LinkedIn previously used a threshold Tskip to identify 'skipped' updates, where users quickly decide to continue scrolling without engaging. This threshold was effective across different types of updates and was incorporated into the Passive Optimization framework as a negative signal in the Multi-Objective Optimization (MOO) function."
    },
    {
      "title": "Challenges in Modeling 'Long Dwell' Behavior",
      "content": "Modeling 'long dwell' behavior presented several challenges, including noisy dwell time signals, lack of adaptive thresholds, and biases introduced by static thresholds. These challenges required the development of novel approaches to address noise, develop adaptive thresholds, and avoid biases in content promotion."
    },
    {
      "title": "Auto Normalized Long Dwell Model",
      "content": "LinkedIn developed a binary classifier that predicts whether a user will spend more time on a post compared to a specific percentile of similar posts. The model uses normalization techniques to address bias and noise in dwell time data. It dynamically calculates percentiles based on top-K attributes such as content type, creator type, and distribution method, ensuring adaptability to changes in user behavior and content distribution."
    },
    {
      "title": "Results and Impact",
      "content": "The new model showed significant improvements in user engagement metrics, including sessions, overall time spent, and time spent per post. The model's dynamic nature allows it to evolve alongside the ecosystem, accommodating changes in user behavior and content distributions. Online A/B testing confirmed the model's effectiveness, with statistically significant positive improvements in the target dwell time metrics."
    },
    {
      "title": "Future Work",
      "content": "LinkedIn plans to further improve the value of dwell time modeling by understanding biases and feature penetration, as well as leveraging causal inference techniques for modeling long-term engagement. The work described in this article is part of a broader strategy to incorporate dwell time into AI models to enhance the LinkedIn Feed experience for all members."
    }
  ],
  "conclusion": "The development of the Auto Normalized Long Dwell Model has significantly improved user engagement on the LinkedIn Feed by addressing the challenges of noisy signals, static thresholds, and biases. The model's dynamic and adaptive nature ensures it can evolve with the ecosystem, providing a more personalized and engaging experience for all members. LinkedIn continues to explore new methods to enhance the value of dwell time modeling, aiming to further improve content ranking and user retention."
}

