{
  "title": "Temporal Fusion Transformer for Demand Forecasting at Picnic",
  "summary": "This article details Picnic's implementation of the Temporal Fusion Transformer (TFT) for demand forecasting. The model was adopted to improve forecast precision, especially for slow-moving items, and to provide interpretable predictions and uncertainty estimates. The article outlines the model's architecture, the challenges faced during adoption, and the benefits realized.",
  "key_points": [
    {
      "title": "Motivation for TFT Adoption",
      "content": "Picnic transitioned from gradient boosting models and LSTMs to TFT due to limitations in handling complex temporal patterns and uncertainty. The TFT's ability to incorporate static and dynamic features, provide explainability, and generate prediction intervals made it a suitable choice for operational forecasting."
    },
    {
      "title": "TFT Architecture Overview",
      "content": "The TFT model is a transformer-based neural network designed for multi-horizon time series forecasting. It includes components such as Gated Residual Networks (GRNs), static covariate encoders, variable selection networks, a local encoder-decoder, a temporal fusion decoder, and quantile regression for prediction intervals."
    },
    {
      "title": "Model Components and Functionality",
      "content": [
        "Gated Residual Networks (GRNs): Used throughout the model to add adaptability and residual connections for efficient learning.",
        "Static Covariate Encoders: Integrate static metadata into the model to enrich temporal representations.",
        "Variable Selection Networks: Help identify the most relevant features for prediction and reduce noise.",
        "Local Encoder-Decoder: Focuses on short-term context using LSTM-based sequence-to-sequence architecture.",
        "Temporal Fusion Decoder: Combines short-term and long-term dependencies using self-attention mechanisms for interpretability.",
        "Quantile Regression: Generates prediction intervals to quantify uncertainty at each time step."
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Implementation and Challenges",
      "content": [
        "Picnic implemented two TFT models: one for article-level demand forecasting and another for delivery-level forecasting.",
        "Initial implementation used PyTorch Forecasting, but the team is considering switching to Darts for better maintenance and flexibility.",
        "Challenges included limited online resources, high memory usage during training, and the need for GPU-based computation.",
        "Sampling techniques were used to manage training data size, and training times were significantly longer compared to simpler models."
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Results and Benefits",
      "content": [
        "The TFT model improved forecast precision by 20%, particularly for slow-moving items.",
        "Explainability features helped communicate model behavior to stakeholders and guide model development.",
        "Prediction intervals enabled better operational decisions by balancing waste and unavailability."
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Lessons Learned",
      "content": [
        "Embrace the Learning Curve: Implementing a complex model like TFT requires time and effort to understand and tailor it to the use case.",
        "Consider Hardware Costs: Deep learning models require significant computational resources, so the benefits must justify the investment.",
        "Start Simple: Begin with simpler models like gradient boosting and only move to advanced models if necessary.",
        "Stay Curious: The ML landscape is rapidly evolving, and newer models like TiDe may offer further improvements."
      ]
    }
  ],
  "conclusion": "The adoption of the Temporal Fusion Transformer at Picnic has led to significant improvements in demand forecasting accuracy and operational decision-making. The model's interpretability and uncertainty quantification have been particularly valuable in a business context. The team continues to explore new models and techniques to further enhance forecasting performance."
}

